o RetroArch/SyncThing setup. Free tier.","done":false},{"text":"Cons: $12/mo. Small team. Discord under 100 members. Volatile longevity.","done":false},{"text":"Alt visual: RetroAssembly - prettier but fewer systems/features","done":false},{"text":"Alt self-hosted: RomM - host your own collection","done":false}]}],"broll":[{"text":"Playing on retro handheld, cloud save to phone, then PC, then PS5 controller - seamless flow","done":false},{"text":"Koin running on big screen TV via Android TV box with PS5 controller","done":false},{"text":"Drag-and-drop ROM upload on browser","done":false},{"text":"Retro Achievement popping up on screen","done":false}],"createdAt":0},{"id":"gamenative","title":"GameNative: PC Games on Android","status":"Idea","targetDate":"","postedDate":"","hook":"Show a demanding PC game (Elden Ring, GTA V, Cyberpunk) running on a handheld Android device, no context yet. Your entire Steam, GOG, and Epic library. On your handheld. Natively. For free.","outro":"GitHub links in description, subscribe, merch.","notes":"Title: The Best Way To Play ALL Your PC Games On Android. Thumbnail: Steam, GOG, Epic icons. Huge recognisable game titles. GitHub: https://github.com/utkarshdalal/GameNative. Performance fork (SD 8 Gen 2+): https://github.com/maxjivi05/GameNative-Performance. Differentiator: simplest setup guide on YouTube plus Thor 2nd screen as touchpad plus performance fork demo.","seoTitle":"The Best Way To Play ALL Your PC Games On Android","targetLength":"12-18 mins","retentionStrategy":"problem-solution","flowSteps":[{"name":"Simple Setup Guide","done":false,"bullets":[{"text":"Step 1: Download APK from GitHub releases - show exactly where","done":false},{"text":"Step 2: Install, grant install unknown apps permission","done":false},{"text":"Step 3: Log in with Steam QR code","done":false},{"text":"Step 4: Sync libraries - Steam, GOG, Epic all in one place","done":false},{"text":"Step 5: Install a game - download direct from storefront","done":false}]},{"name":"Performance Optimisation","done":false,"bullets":[{"text":"Install custom Turnip GPU drivers via Driver Manager","done":false},{"text":"Set resolution to 720p in Modify Default Config","done":false},{"text":"Use Known Configs for specific games (3-dot menu)","done":false},{"text":"Cap frame rate via DXVK_FRAME_RATE to prevent throttling","done":false},{"text":"A2-rated SD card for external storage","done":false}]},{"name":"Performance Fork (SD 8 Gen 2+)","done":false,"bullets":[{"text":"Explain the community performance fork - maxjivi05 on GitHub","done":false},{"text":"Show aggressive clock management forcing GPU to max power","done":false},{"text":"Side-by-side: standard vs performance fork on same game","done":false}]},{"name":"Touchpad and Mouse Tips","done":false,"bullets":[{"text":"AYN Thor: use 2nd screen as a trackpad for mouse-heavy games","done":false},{"text":"Other solutions: gyro mouse, touch overlay, USB trackpad","done":false}]},{"name":"Pros and Cons","done":false,"bullets":[{"text":"Pros: Native play, unified library, true offline, free and open source, built-in controls","done":false},{"text":"Cons: Tinkering required, not every game works, needs powerful chip, storage intensive","done":false}]}],"broll":[{"text":"Demanding PC game running on handheld - no context yet","done":false},{"text":"Screen capture: GitHub releases page - download APK","done":false},{"text":"Screen capture: Driver Manager - installing Turnip drivers","done":false},{"text":"AYN Thor 2nd screen used as trackpad in a mouse-heavy game","done":false}],"createdAt":1},{"id":"dock-style","title":"Dock Style Comparison","status":"Idea","targetDate":"","postedDate":"","hook":"Put each dock down on the table one by one - a number appears above it on screen as each one lands. Intro script welcoming viewers, explaining structure from simplest to most complex.","outro":"Best budget = HDMI with Power. Best overall = Jumpgate. Best for power users = UGREEN. Do not buy more than you need! Mention the two free bonus solutions before signing off. Subscribe, AliExpress and Amazon links in description.","notes":"## Titles\\n1. The Best Handheld Dock\\n2. What Handheld Dock Do You Need?\\n3. One Dock To Rule Them All\\n\\n## Thumbnail\\nHolding the Jumpgate dock in the middle, glowing edge, all kinds of handhelds around it (Steam Deck, Switch 2, MacBook).\\n\\n## Target Audience\\nHandheld gamers (Switch, Steam Deck, Retroid) and laptop users wanting a portable desk setup.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## HDMI Version Cheat Sheet\\n\\n| HDMI Version | Max 4K | Max 1440p | Max 1080p | Typically found on |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| HDMI 1.4 | 4K@30Hz | 1440p@60Hz | 1080p@120Hz | Budget docks, mini-HDMI ports |\\n| HDMI 2.0 | 4K@60Hz | 1440p@144Hz | 1080p@240Hz | Mid-range docks, most monitor main ports |\\n| HDMI 2.1 | 4K@120Hz | 1440p@240Hz | 1080p@480Hz | Jumpgate, premium docks |\\n\\n**Key tip:** Always check the HDMI version on the *specific port* \\u2014 a monitor\'s mini-HDMI is often HDMI 1.4 even if the main port is 2.1.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## USB-C / DisplayPort Alt Mode \\u2014 Monitor Spec Check\\n\\n| Look for on spec sheet | What it means |\\n|---|---|\\n| DisplayPort Alt Mode / DP Alt Mode | USB-C port can output video \\u2014 essential |\\n| DP 1.2 over USB-C | Up to 4K@60Hz or 1440p@144Hz |\\n| DP 1.4 over USB-C | Up to 4K@120Hz or 1440p@165Hz (UPerfect C2) |\\n| DP 2.0/2.1 over USB-C (Thunderbolt) | Up to 4K@144Hz or 1440p@240Hz+ |\\n| No mention of DP Alt Mode | No video output \\u2014 USB-C is power/data only |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Cable Cheat Sheet (USB-C to USB-C)\\n\\n| Cable standard | Bandwidth | Carries | Max output |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| USB 3.1 / 3.2 Gen 1 | 5 Gbps | DP 1.2 | 4K@60Hz / 1440p@144Hz |\\n| USB 3.2 Gen 2 | 10 Gbps | DP 1.4 | 4K@120Hz / 1440p@165Hz |\\n| Thunderbolt 3/4 or USB4 | 40 Gbps | DP 2.0/2.1 | 4K@144Hz / 1440p@240Hz+ |\\n\\n**UPerfect C2:** Likely DP 1.4 \\u2014 a USB 3.2 Gen 2 C-to-C cable is all you need for high-refresh 2K.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What to say on camera (intro to Dock 1)\\n\\"Before we get into HDMI cables \\u2014 if your monitor has a USB-C port with DisplayPort Alt Mode, a C-to-C cable can often hit higher refresh rates than HDMI. Check your monitor spec sheet: look for DP Alt Mode on the USB-C input, and double-check what HDMI version the mini-HDMI port actually is \\u2014 it is not always the same as the main port.\\"\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Description Links\\nUPerfect C2 monitor, Jumpgate dock, UGREEN dock, Retroid dock, USB-C to HDMI cables","seoTitle":"The Best Handheld Dock","targetLength":"12-15 mins","retentionStrategy":"cheap-to-expensive","flowSteps":[{"name":"Reference: HDMI & USB-C Cheat Sheets (on-screen graphics)","md":"## HDMI Version Cheat Sheet\\n\\n| HDMI Version | Max 4K | Max 1440p | Max 1080p | Typically found on |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| HDMI 1.4 | 4K@30Hz | 1440p@60Hz | 1080p@120Hz | Budget docks, most mini-HDMI ports |\\n| HDMI 2.0 | 4K@60Hz | 1440p@144Hz | 1080p@240Hz | Mid-range docks, most monitor main ports |\\n| HDMI 2.1 | 4K@120Hz | 1440p@240Hz | 1080p@480Hz | Jumpgate, premium docks |\\n\\n**Key tip:** Always check the HDMI version on the *specific port* -- a monitor\'s mini-HDMI is often 1.4 even if the main port is 2.1.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## USB-C / DisplayPort Alt Mode\\n\\n| Look for on spec sheet | What it means |\\n| --- | --- |\\n| DisplayPort Alt Mode / DP Alt Mode | USB-C port can output video -- essential |\\n| DP 1.2 over USB-C | Up to 4K@60Hz or 1440p@144Hz |\\n| DP 1.4 over USB-C | Up to 4K@120Hz or 1440p@165Hz (UPerfect C2) |\\n| DP 2.0/2.1 (Thunderbolt) | Up to 4K@144Hz or 1440p@240Hz+ |\\n| No DP Alt Mode listed | No video output -- USB-C is power/data only |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Cable Cheat Sheet (USB-C to USB-C)\\n\\n| Cable standard | Bandwidth | Carries | Max output |\\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\\n| USB 3.1 / 3.2 Gen 1 | 5 Gbps | DP 1.2 | 4K@60Hz / 1440p@144Hz |\\n| USB 3.2 Gen 2 | 10 Gbps | DP 1.4 | 4K@120Hz / 1440p@165Hz |\\n| Thunderbolt 3/4 or USB4 | 40 Gbps | DP 2.0/2.1 | 4K@144Hz / 1440p@240Hz+ |\\n\\n**UPerfect C2:** DP 1.4 -- a USB 3.2 Gen 2 C-to-C cable unlocks full high-refresh 2K.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What to say on camera\\n\\n> If your monitor has a USB-C port with DisplayPort Alt Mode, a C-to-C cable can often hit higher refresh rates than HDMI. Check your monitor spec sheet -- look for DP Alt Mode on the USB-C input, and double-check what HDMI version the mini-HDMI port actually is. It is not always the same as the main port.","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"B-Roll: Turntable & Table Lineup","md":"## Shots to get\\n- [ ] Each cable/dock spinning on the turntable (one at a time, clean loop)\\n- [ ] Place each cable/dock onto the table one at a time until the table is filled with all of them \\u2014 film as one continuous or edited sequence","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 1: USB-C to HDMI Cable ($4.46)","md":"## Script\\nFirst up is the simplest option \\u2014 just a USB-C to HDMI cable. Show how the RP6 struggled to output 4K@60Hz to the TV without being given extra power. That leads us into option 2.\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] RP6 struggling at 4K60 \\u2014 show the drop/stutter\\n- [ ] Cable close-up on turntable","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 2: USB-C to HDMI with Charging ($9.83)","md":"## Script\\nOption 2 is the USB-C to HDMI cable WITH POWER. That extra power through the included USB-C port on the adapter gives the RP6 the juice it needs to run flawlessly. This cable is also advertised to work with the Switch 2 \\u2014 and it works great! Excellent performance for under $10, and also neatly tucked away.\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] RP6 running flawlessly with the powered adapter (contrast with Dock 1)\\n- [ ] Switch 2 connected and working\\n- [ ] Show the USB-C charging port on the adapter","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 3: Simple Connector Apple Style ($5.86)","md":"## Script\\nNext up is this small adapter, which is neat \\u2014 but unfortunately the performance lets it down. Worth noting it\'s the same brand as the previous one, but this is the older version now. A new version could be a good option!\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] Show the adapter\\n- [ ] Demonstrate the performance limitation","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 4: Nintendo Switch Themed Connector ($5.41)","md":"## Script\\nNext up we have the knock-off scam. This is a clear knockoff of a well-known product \\u2014 the Apple video adapter \\u2014 which may attract people who don\'t know much about this stuff. This one doesn\'t even work. Absolutely terrible.\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] Show the product\\n- [ ] Attempt to use it \\u2014 show it failing\\n- [ ] Side-by-side with the real Apple adapter if possible","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 5: Retroid Handheld Dock ($29.90)","md":"## Script\\nNext up we have an actual dock made by one of the handheld companies \\u2014 Retroid. This one works great with Retroid products, although it must be said that due to the RP6\'s USB-C port being off-centre to the left, it doesn\'t actually sit perfectly. The Steam Deck has to go in upside down and is very awkward \\u2014 and it doesn\'t work with the Switch 2 at all. I don\'t recommend this. So what do I recommend?\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] RP6 in the dock \\u2014 show the off-centre issue\\n- [ ] Steam Deck going in upside down \\u2014 show the awkwardness\\n- [ ] Switch 2 failing to connect","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 6: Jumpgate Generic Dock ($40.00) - THE WINNER","md":"## Script\\nTHIS is THE WINNER. The Jumpgate works with everything and has so many great features at a great price. This has been the dock everyone\'s been suggesting for a while, and it\'s the reason I made this video.\\n\\nIt has Switch 2 support, so it becomes a much lower-profile alternative to the original Switch 2 dock \\u2014 which covers my TV when it\'s not in use. The piece that goes into the Switch 2 can be removed and the USB-C port can be moved, so it can fit almost any handheld. Works great with the RP6.\\n\\nAnd the best part \\u2014 the actual USB hub with all the ports can be easily removed so it can work for anything else too, like the Steam Deck or even a laptop. It\'s like the one I showed earlier in the video, but actually good.\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] Full feature tour \\u2014 show the removable insert and repositionable USB-C\\n- [ ] RP6 connected and running\\n- [ ] Switch 2 connected (compare size vs official dock next to TV)\\n- [ ] USB hub detached and used separately\\n- [ ] Steam Deck connected","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Dock 7: UGREEN Steam Deck 9-in-1 Dock ($59.99)","md":"## Script\\nOur next option is the UGREEN 9-in-1 Steam Deck Dock. This one has the most ports and features of any dock in this video \\u2014 pretty much anything you could possibly need. It could be a great choice if you want to turn your Steam Deck into a docked PC.\\n\\nIt has ports for connecting keyboard and mouse wireless dongles, SD cards and microSD cards, multiple USB devices, Ethernet \\u2014 and of course it turns into a dock for the Steam Deck.\\n\\nIt does have downsides though. The cable solution isn\'t very elegant \\u2014 it often gets stuck and sometimes falls out when the dock part is opened. It doesn\'t work great with other handhelds that have the USB-C port on the bottom, since it\'s made for the Steam Deck. It\'s quite large if you\'re just using it as a hub for a laptop or computer, and it needs more cables than other docks because it doesn\'t have a built-in USB-C connector.\\n\\nThe connection is rock solid though and it\'s a fantastic performer \\u2014 so if you feel the form factor would work for you, it\'s a really solid choice.\\n\\n## Shots\\n- [ ] Full port tour\\n- [ ] Steam Deck docked\\n- [ ] Show the cable getting stuck / falling out\\n- [ ] Show the size compared to other docks","done":false,"bullets":[]},{"name":"Bonus: Free Solutions Worth Knowing","md":"## Script: USB-C Cable (Free Option 1)\\nThose all cost money \\u2014 but with the current financial climate, I\'d like to recommend a couple of potentially free options you may already have lying around.\\n\\nThe first is just a simple USB-C cable. If you have a monitor with a USB-C input \\u2014 like a portable monitor or a computer monitor \\u2014 you might already be set. My computer monitor had a USB-C input and I didn\'t even realise until making this video, so have a look!\\n\\nYou can simply connect many handhelds with just a high-speed USB-C cable. I\'m using a 3.2 cable here. You\'ll want to make sure it supports DisplayPort Alt Mode and isn\'t only for charging. Most monitors will also passthrough charging to your device \\u2014 and in many cases, this USB-C connection offers even higher framerates than other connectors. So that\'s definitely worth checking out.\\n\\n### Shots\\n- [ ] Show the USB-C port on the monitor\\n- [ ] Connect handheld with just the cable \\u2014 show it working\\n- [ ] Show the higher refresh rate vs HDMI\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Script: scrcpy (Free Option 2)\\nAnother free option for Android handhelds is scrcpy \\u2014 pronounced \\"screencopy\\"... somehow. This allows you to view your Android device on your Windows, Mac, or Linux computer.\\n\\nJust grab the free app from GitHub \\u2014 linked in the description. Enable USB debugging on your device by going to System Settings, tapping Build Number lots of times, then Developer Options \\u2192 USB Debugging. Connect via USB cable to your PC, accept permissions, and you can now see your device on your computer. This is also an easy way to record or stream it. Just be aware there may be a little more latency this way compared to a dedicated dock.\\n\\n### Shots\\n- [ ] Walk through the USB debugging setup on device\\n- [ ] Connect to PC and show scrcpy running\\n- [ ] Mention the latency caveat\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Final Recommendations\\nMy picks are the **USB-C to HDMI with Power cable** or the **Jumpgate dock**. Both are great!","done":false,"bullets":[]}],"broll":[{"text":"Each dock placed on table one by one with number overlay appearing","done":false},{"text":"Close-ups of port labels (4K 60Hz vs 1080p)","done":false},{"text":"Jumpgate reveal moment - make it feel like the winner announcement","done":false},{"text":"On-screen graphic: HDMI version table (1.4 / 2.0 / 2.1 with max resolutions)","done":false},{"text":"On-screen graphic: USB-C DP Alt Mode cable cheat sheet","done":false},{"text":"UPerfect C2: C-to-C cable vs mini-HDMI side-by-side refresh rate test on camera","done":false},{"text":"scrcpy demo: RP Classic mirrored to Windows PC over USB -- show it working on screen","done":false},{"text":"C-to-C cable plugged into USB-C monitor -- show it just working with no dock","done":false}],"createdAt":2,"_v":5},{"id":"danyang","title":"The Eight Best Views of Danyang, Korea","status":"Idea","targetDate":"","postedDate":"","hook":"I have some bad news but also some great news. The bad news is Danyang is famous for eight beautiful scenic views but they are all really far away from each other and I did not have a car. So the great news is I am going to make my own list of the eight best things to see in Danyang.","outro":"Invite viewers to share their own favourite Danyang spots in the comments. Subscribe to Ryan Korea, links in description.","notes":"Channel: Ryan Korea. Briefly explain the official Danyang Palgyeong (8 scenic cultural landmarks). Honest explainer: spread across a large area, no car = not practical to see all eight in one trip.","seoTitle":"The Eight Best Views of Danyang Korea","targetLength":"8-12 mins","retentionStrategy":"chronological","flowSteps":[{"name":"The Official Eight Views Explained","done":false,"bullets":[{"text":"Briefly explain the official Danyang Palgyeong - eight scenic cultural landmarks","done":false},{"text":"Honest explainer: spread across a large area, no car = not practical to see all eight","done":false},{"text":"Frame y